1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2 c5 $5 {This quick advance was
seen in some recent games as a direct and forcing attempt of solving Black's
opening problems. The line is still very fresh but should not be
underestimated, as it was played even by Carlsen in the last World Cup which
usually means a signal of approval. The main continuation, for now, is the
principled} 6. dxc5 {, grabbing the pawn.} (6. Rc1 {is also logical and was
Martinovic's reaction against Carlsen. Although I think this move is perfectly
fine, I recommend the move order with taking the pawn first as I have
different plans for the c1-square.}) (6. e4 {is pretty harmless for Black in
view of the active reaction} Nxc3 7. Bxc3 cxd4 8. Bxd4 e5 $1 {a nice pawn
sacrifice.} 9. Bxe5 Bb4+ 10. Bc3 ({Of course not} 10. Ke2 $4 Qe7 $1 $19) 10...
Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qa5 $44 {Goryachkina,A (2593)-Chigaev,M (2631) RUS-chT Sochi
2021 (9.1) 1/2-1/2 when practice has proven that Black has enough compensation
for the pawn with quick development and pressure on c3. It is hard to imagine
White risking to be inferior here, but the analysis also shows that it is equally
hard to exploit the small material advantage. In the most recent game in the
database, for example, Black had no problems regaining the pawn.}) 6... Bg7 {
Black is not worried about regaining the pawn immediately. Instead, the idea
is to look for quick development and pressure on White's camp, as White has
not an easy task dealing with the underdeveloped kingside. Here, I recommend
the less exploited} 7. Qc1 $5 {[%csl Yb2,Yc3,Yc5][%cal Gc1h6] which may look a
bit strange, but has some good points. The queen is well placed to defend many
sensible points in White's camp (b2, c3 and the c5-pawn) and makes it possible
to consider Bh6 in some cases getting rid of Black's strong bishop.} (7. Rc1 {
is more natural, of course. The game might continue} O-O 8. Nf3 {and Black has
a choice between forcing an endgame with} Nxc3 ({Or continue developing with} 
8... Nc6 {transposing to a position that was reached in many recent games,
with a satisfactory score for Black.}) 9. Bxc3 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Be6 11. a3 Nd7
12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. e3 Rfc8 14. b4 a5 $44 {[%cal Ga8a2] when even after the
exchanges, White is still underdeveloped and Black's pieces are very active.
Black's play is very easy here and White always struggles to make use of the
pawn. Considering that this position is reached more or less by force, the
text also aims to avoid such endgames.}) (7. Qb3 $2 {looks like a perfect
reaction, but it is in fact a mistake:} Be6 $1 8. Qxb7 O-O $1 {Gretarsson,H 
(2415)-Antipov,M (2558) Selfoss World Champions Group 2019 (8) 0-1 and White
suddenly found himself in trouble. Black soon brought all his pieces into play
and launched a winning attack against the king.} {The computer says the best
option now was to accept the risk and go full materialistic with} 9. Qxa8 {
when after} Qd7 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Yb8c6] White will have to sacrifice his queen
soon. The position remains complex. But in practice, it looks like Black keeps
the best chances in view of White's still poor development.}) 7... O-O {
This position was only reached in three games so far, and all of them followed
this natural path.} (7... Nc6 $146 {is also possible, but allows} 8. e4 Ndb4 9.
a3 $1 Nd3+ 10. Bxd3 Qxd3 11. Nge2 {when White's chances of completing the
development look very decent to me.} Be6 ({In case of} 11... O-O $6 12. Bh6 $1
Be6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%csl Gg7] White has nice chances of exploiting the early
definition of Black's king by means of} 14. h4 $1 {when the attack on the
kingside looks very dangerous. The following line is very instructive:} Qc4 15.
h5 Ne5 16. Qe3 $1 Qxc5 {apparently a clever tactical resource, but after} 17.
Nd4 Bc4 18. O-O-O $1 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Yh5g6,Yf2f4,Gd4f5] Black has to deal
with many dangerous threats and is on the verge of collapsing.}) 12. Bh6 $5 {
A very logical idea as we are happy to get rid of the enemy bishop pair. This
move also poses a practical question to Black as he has to choose between
different approaches.} ({If White castles first} 12. O-O O-O {and now
continues with} 13. Bh6 {Black has the important move} Bb3 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Yd1]
taking control over the d-file and preventing b2-b4, reinforcing the
c5-pawn. Black is likely able to regain the pawn here, for instance:} 14. Bxg7
Kxg7 15. Nf4 Qd4 16. Nce2 $5 Qxe4 17. Qc3+ e5 $1 18. Qxb3 exf4 19. Qxb7 Rab8
$132 {with a dynamic balance.}) 12... Bxh6 ({The natural reaction} 12... O-O $2
{is bad in view of} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. h4 $1 $40 {transposing to 11...0-0. This
is an important point of delaying 0-0 for White.}) (12... Be5 $5 {is possible,
keeping the strong dark-squared bishop. However, Black is likely going to
castle long now, ensuring a double-edged game. After} 13. O-O O-O-O {the
engine is always sceptical and evaluates the position as equal, but the game
goes on and the position might become sharp at any moment. For instance:} 14.
Nf4 Qc4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 $5 {this recapture ensures that Black will recover the
pawn.} 16. Bf4 Qxc5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Qe3 Kb8 19. Rac1 {[%csl Ge6,Ge7][%cal
Yc3a4,Ya4c5] and as I said, the game goes on. Both sides have chances, but I
like White's chances in practice due to the unbalanced structure and prospects
of getting some pressure on the queenside.}) (12... Bxc3+ $6 {is a somewhat
counterintuitive and drastic measure.} 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. Nxc3 O-O-O 15. f3
Rd3 16. Kf2 Rhd8 17. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Yc5] Perhaps this endgame is a draw with
correct play, but White is still a pawn up and has no problems. In practice,
we are never risking anything here, and sometimes Black's position can become
worse in case of imprecise play.}) 13. Qxh6 {Now} O-O-O $1 14. O-O Qd2 $1 {
seems the best way of exploiting Black's lead in development. However, White
has a very strong idea here:} 15. Nf4 $1 {looking for active play.} ({The
endgame after} 15. Qxd2 Rxd2 16. b4 Bc4 17. Rfe1 Rhd8 $44 {leaves Black with
more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 15... Bc4 ({In case of} 15...
Qxb2 $2 16. Nfd5 $1 {[%csl Rb2] the queen is suddenly at risk of being trapped
and after} Bxd5 17. exd5 $1 Qxc3 18. dxc6 bxc6 19. Qf4 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal
Ga1b1] the weakness of Black's king is a serious problem.}) 16. Rfe1 {The
position is already tenser than it looks, but it is Black who needs to be
more careful here. For example:} Qxb2 (16... e5 $2 {does not work in view of}
17. Qh3+ $1 {[%cal Gf4d5] and the knight finds an excellent outpost on d5 on
the next move.}) ({So} 16... Kb8 {seems to be a useful prophylactic move that
also prepares e7-e5, but White is still better after} 17. Rad1 $1 Qxb2 18. Nfd5
{[%cal Gd1b1,Gh6f4] with dangerous threats like Rb1 or Qf4. The safest option
seems to be to go for simplifications with} Bxd5 {but after} 19. exd5 Qxc3 20.
dxc6 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 bxc6 22. Qf4+ {[%csl Rb8] the exposed king makes Black's
position unpleasant again.}) {Now follows a series of strong moves by White:}
17. Nfd5 $1 e6 18. Reb1 $1 Qc2 19. Rc1 $1 Qd3 ({But not} 19... Qb2 $4 20. Na4
$1 Qd4 21. Ndb6+ $1 axb6 22. Nxb6+ Kb8 23. Nxc4 $18) ({Or} 19... Qb3 20. Nb4 $1
Nxb4 21. axb4 $18 {[%cal Ga1a7]}) 20. Ne3 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3] and Black's position
seems very weird. The queen is almost trapped. Even though we do not see
direct threats for White here yet, Black's play still looks harder. A possible
variation which illustrates this feeling is} Rd7 (20... Nd4 {looks more active,
but is well met by} 21. Qg7 $1 Nb3 22. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd3]}) 21. a4 Rhd8 22. h3
(22. Nxc4 Qxc4 23. Nb5 {does not works due to the nice resource} Qxc5 $1) 22...
Kb8 (22... Ba6 23. Qxh7 $16 {is simply better for White.}) 23. Qf4+ Ka8 24.
Nxc4 Qxc4 25. Nd5 $1 e5 $8 26. Qh4 $18 {[%cal Rh4h7] and White wins. After
checking all these lines it seems that 12...Be5 is probably Black's best
option, but as we can see the positions are often of a non-forcing nature and
White has some thematic ideas to fight for an advantage.}) ({The slightly
awkward} 7... Nf6 $6 $146 {is also suggested by the engine, with the idea of
