21. Bf3 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rb7] is obviously worse.}) 21. Rfd1 $1 (21. Qxa7 {
is well met by} Rc2 $1 22. Qxd4 Bxd4 $44 {[%csl Gd4] when the strong bishop
and active rook give Black at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 21...
Qxe4 22. Bf3 Qc2 $1 23. Qxa7 Rc7 24. Qe3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4,Yf3] The forced
sequence has come to an end resulting in a balanced endgame. Still, from a
practical point of view, I think White has some ideas to play for an advantage
like fixing the b7-pawn as a weakness by means of b5-b6 or creating a distant
passed pawn on the a-file. Also, we should not forget that opposite-coloured
bishop's positions with heavy pieces on the board are very rich and offer many
possibilities for both sides. I will not pretend that my recommendation is
some kind of refutation against 5...c5, especially because the line is still
very fresh and future tournament practice is required to understand it better.
Nevertheless, I firmly believe that 7.Qc1!? is a nice way of catching your
opponent off guard in a not so popular line especially if you know the key
ideas to solve the issues of White's position.} *

