Nc3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4,Ge4f6] and Black is in trouble.}) 15... Be6 $1 (15...
Nxf3+ 16. gxf3 Be6 {is less precise due to the nice reply} 17. Bb4 $1 Qf6 ({
But not} 17... c5 $2 18. Qc3 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rg7]}) 18. Qc3 Qxc3+ 19. Bxc3
$14 {[%csl Gc3,Gf1] when the bishop pair still offers better chances for White.
}) (15... Nd3+ $2 {is simply bad now, as after} 16. Bxd3 Rxd3 17. O-O {[%csl
Rg8][%cal Ya1d1] White has completed the development and soon starts to
exploit Black's weak king. The following variation is a nice example:} Be6 18.
Qc2 Bf5 19. Rad1 $1 Rxe3 20. Qc1 $1 Re4 21. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 $16 {[%csl Gg8]
and Black is already in trouble.}) 16. Qb4 $5 ({In case of} 16. Qc2 Bf5 {
White should repeat moves or take some risks in the line} 17. e4 $6 Nc6 $5 18.
Bd3 Nb4 19. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 20. Kf1 Bg4 $13 {with a double-edged game.}) 16... Qxb4
(16... c5 {is met by} 17. Qh4 $1 {when Black can't avoid the queen's exchange.}
(17. Qe4 $5)) 17. Bxb4 Nxf3+ {The right exchange, though not totally obvious.}
(17... Nd3+ {is the other option, exchanging the knight for the bishop.
However, after} 18. Bxd3 Rxd3 19. Bc3 $14 {[%csl Gf6,Rh7][%cal Yf3g5,Yg5e4]
White still has slightly better chances. The White knight can be very
dangerous in such positions, that's why Black should exchange it.}) 18. gxf3 {
This endgame should be balanced with correct play, but the game goes on and we
have an interesting imbalance on the board. From White's perspective, I like
the bishop pair, and the doubled pawns are not weak, instead, they can be
useful to grab more space in the centre and to provoke open lines on the
kingside at some point. The following variation looks very logical:} Nd5 19.
Bd2 c5 20. a3 f6 {Black understandably wants to place some pawns on the dark
squares in order to limit the enemy bishop. Now It's White's turn of improving
the structure by means of} 21. e4 Ne7 22. Rc1 b6 (22... Rac8 $2 23. Be3 b6 24.
Ba6 $1 Rc6 25. O-O $16 {is already unpleasant for Black.}) 23. Bc3 (23. b4 $5)
23... Kf7 24. f4 $1 Nc6 25. f3 $14 {[%cal Ye1f2,Yh1g1,Gf4f5] When we have a
long way ahead, but White's position still looks a little bit more pleasant to
me. Black should avoid careless advances as that could open more lines for the
enemy bishops. On the other hand, White can slowly improve his pieces. The
breakthrough f4-f5 is an interesting idea in many positions especially if the
rook is already on g1. Of course, this is by no means a conclusive assessment
of 7.h4, and further tournament practice is needed to provide a proper
evaluation of this move. Nevertheless, I think It's an interesting attempt of
posing new problems for Black, mainly because many players can be caught
unprepared in such a fresh line.} *

