and the game goes on. The position is objectively balanced, but the passed
pawn always keeps some chances for White, and the advance h4-h5 is an
interesting way of posing more practical problems for Black. The line 11...Nc6
seems a solid and reliable path to equalize, so I tried to offer a few ideas
to make Black's task harder in a practical game. As usual, only further
tournament games can prove how useful are these ideas.} *

