Ke3 Kf6 {The king would have to retreat in the next move anyway. There's still
a long way ahead but after} 26. f4 $14 {[%cal Ye4e5,Yh3h4,Gc3e4,Yf4f5] I like
White's practical chances. The endgame is obviously balanced with correct play
for both sides, but in practice looks like there are more useful ideas
available for White: we can increase the tension on the kingside with h3-h4,
and Black should be aware of both advances e4-e5 and f4-f5, grabbing more
space and pushing his pieces back. The e5 advance is especially dangerous if
White has the chance of improving the knight by using the e4-square. To
conclude this chapter, I would like to say that all lines seen here look
interesting for me, and I've only chosen this one as the main line because it
has more games in the database. Which option suits better to you is more a
matter of taste: you can look for a complex middlegame rich in possibilities
for both sides (8.Bb5) or test your technique on a balanced game with no risk
and some practical chances (9.Nf3).} (26. b4 $5 {is also possible, but after}
a5 27. b5 Rc8 {the position seems more double-edged.}) *

